Hidden inside the leaves of a willow tree
You can see a firey zircon stone, an old wheelbarrow, a short piece of wire, a golden statue, a golden monkey, a cat's eye gem, a jasper pebble, a chest full of gold coins, a golden crown, an enormous jewel and an orb.
You can go out.

You put all the valuable objects in the wheelbarrow and make your way back down the mountain...

  As you descend the slopes, satisfied that your quest is at an end, you are flanked once again by the old hermit walking along a short distance from you.
"You have done well... although, I suspect that there is a part of you that has never left the mountain, and perhaps never will." The bedraggled old man leaves you.

  The local people are shocked to behold your return - they had abandoned you to death and are somewhat elated and over the coming days, fascinated by the tales you have to tell. Your tales though are selectively chosen - after all, some things are better left unsaid.

  An old dwarf reportedly travelled through some time ago, speaking whistful thoughts in a loud voice, an air of command about him. You decide to do as Merlon did and
move on from this place, friendly though it is, despite being happy enough. After all you are now rich - hardly suited for village life.

  However, after making away one afternoon you soon make a surprise return and announce to the local folk that you have changed your mind and decided to stay. They are overjoyed and you maintain a pretense of normal behaviour for the rest of that evening until you retire; though inside you a deep uncertainty looms. As you left the village, your body had become slightly transparent and this increased the further away from EELTAIL you dared. Along with this came a strong feeling of being pulled away to a dark forest. Knowing that to leave EELTAIL is to leave the world as you know it, you have no choice but to accept your fate and remain where you are.

  Many years pass... you live a happy peaceful married life. Now and again you seek solitude from your family to fondle your riches. The more you do this and measure them against the blessings in your new life, the less valuable to you these objects become.
 THE END

The wood on the fire cracks!
